The paper deals with the capacity of index coding, which is a problem in information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves graph theory and combinatorics, which suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) as likely sub-categories. The paper also deals with the structural properties of the confusion graph, which is a type of side information graph, indicating cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the lexicographic product of side information graphs, which is a type of graph product, suggesting cs.CC (Computational Complexity) as a possible sub-category.
